  "eprint": {
    "title": "Secure k-ish nearest neighbors classifier",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Hayim Shaul",
        "email": "shaul@gmail",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Dan Feldman",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Daniela Rus",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "The $k$-nearest neighbors ($k$NN) classifier predicts a class of a query, $q$, by taking the majority class of its $k$ neighbors in an existing (already classified) database, $S$.\nIn secure $k$NN, $q$ and $S$ are owned by two different parties and $q$ is classified without sharing data.\nIn this work we present a classifier based on $k$NN, that is more efficient to implement with homomorphic encryption (HE).\nThe efficiency of our classifier comes from a relaxation we make to consider $\\kappa$ nearest neighbors for\n$\\kappa\\approx k$ with probability that increases as the statistical distance between Gaussian and the distribution of the distances from $q$ to $S$ decreases.\nWe call our classifier $k$-ish Nearest Neighbors ($k$-ish NN).\nFor the implementation\nwe introduce {\\em double-blinded coin-toss} where\nthe bias and output of the toss are encrypted.\nWe use it to approximate the average and variance of the distances from $q$ to $S$\nin a scalable circuit whose depth is independent of $|S|$.\nWe believe these to be of independent interest.\nWe implemented our classifier in an open source library based on HElib and tested it on a breast tumor database.\nOur classifier has accuracy and running time comparable to current state of the art (non-HE) MPC solution that have better running time but worse communication complexity.\nIt also has communication complexity similar to naive HE implementation that have worse running time.",
    "keywords": [
      "FHE",
      "secure machine learning",
      "classification"
    ],
    "category": "Applications",
    "publication_info": "Published elsewhere. pets",
    "last_updated": "2020-03-15",
    "license": "CC BY",
    "related_papers": []
  }
